caption: Soliciting calls of a female and compound hooting of a male.
Tu-whit, tu-whoo call, a variation of a poorly known call primarily used outside the breeding season. Also, some bill-snapping.
Calls of an autumn migrant. Background: Lesser Black-backed Gull Larus fuscus, European Robin Erithacus rubecula, Fieldfare Turdus pilaris and Eurasian Magpie Pica pica.

Two autumn migrants, one near and one far, calling to each other from a distance. Background: Common Chiffchaff Phylloscopus collybita, Eurasian Blue Tit Cyanistes caeruleus and Eurasian Magpie Pica pica.

site_name: Our Lady's Island Lake, Wexford, Ireland
caption: Calls on taking off. Background: Dunlin Calidris alpina and Common Tern Sterna hirundo.

Multiple-note calls on taking off, then single note keek calls in flight. Background: Eurasian Wigeon Mareca penelope, Eurasian Oystercatcher Haematopus ostralegus, Common Redshank Tringa totanus and distant tractor.
Typical calls of an adult in flight over its tundra breeding territory, recorded at close range. Background: another Grey Plover singing.
Nocturnal flight calls of at least two individuals. Background: Redwing Turdus iliacus.

Flight calls of a first-summer, the easier type of flight call to identify. Background: Common Ringed Plover Charadrius hiaticula, Northern Lapwing Vanellus vanellus, Meadow Pipit Anthus pratensis and Common Reed Bunting Emberiza schoeniclus.
Flight calls of a wintering bird passing at close range. Background: Crested Lark Galerida cristata and Delicate Prinia Prinia lepida.
Song of a male. Background: Killdeer Charadrius vociferus, California Gull Larus californicus and Savannah Sparrow Passerculus sandwichensis.
Song of a male. Background: Crested Lark Galerida cristata, Greater Short-toed Lark Calandrella brachydactyla, Black-headed Wagtail Motacilla feldegg and Corn Bunting Emberiza calandra.
Flight calls of a migrating individual. Background: European Robin Erithacus rubecula.

site_name: Betancuria, south of El Cotillo, Fuerteventura, Canary Islands
caption: Booming of displaying male with a dominant frequency of 107 Hz. Background: Berthelot's Pipit Anthus berthelotii and Mediterranean Short-toed Lark Alaudala rufescens.

After a series of faint up sounds as it gulps air, this male gives five loud 'booms', foghorn-like sounds around 141 Hz. Before each boom we can hear a quieter, higher note at 200 Hz where the bird seems to be inhaling; the first boom is preceded by two of these plus a brief lower note at around 122 Hz. The five booms produced by this male are all of the same strength, suggesting that it is in good condition and most likely an adult. Background: Marsh Frog Pelophylax ridibunda.
Rolled song of a female, with energy peaking at around 360 Hz. Background: European Goldfinch Carduelis carduelis.

Compound hooting of two males with soliciting calls of a female, the male's energy peaking at around 860 Hz. From 0:39, aggressive duet of male and female in response to a more distant male. Background: acorns falling, and Fallow Deer Dama dama.

site_name: Vale da Ribeira das Mercês, São Bras de Alportel, Portugal
caption: Hooting of four males, converging around 1.35 kHz. Background: crickets and Mediterranean Tree Frog Hyla meridionalis.
Flight calls of a single individual in flight, with the energy peaking at around 2.3 kHz. Background: Common Snipe Gallinago gallinago and European Robin Erithacus rubecula.

At 4.8 kHz, the sustained whistles of this nervous adult, heard from 8 sec into the recording, are just over twice as high as the calls of Eurasian Whimbrel Numenius phaeopus heard in the preceding recording.

site_name: Hauts Plateaux du Vercors, Drôme, France
caption: The main frequency around which this adult male spins its cyclical song is 7 kHz. Background: European Robin Erithacus rubecula and Eurasian Coal Tit Periparus ater.
Courtship song with 'electric' notes reaching 13 kHz. Background: Sardinian Warbler Sylvia melanocephala, Common Nightingale Luscinia megarhynchos and European Goldfinch Carduelis carduelis.
Reeling song. Main frequency 6 kHz, pulse rate 24/sec. Background: Mallard Anas platyrhynchos and Common Tern Sterna hirundo.

site_name: Karazhar field station, Aqmola Oblast, Kazakhstan
caption: Reeling song. Main frequency 4 kHz, pulse rate 48/sec. Background: Paddyfield Warbler Acrocephalus agricola.
Upward-inflected calls of several birds. Background: a flock of quietly chattering Dunlin Calidris alpina.

Downward-inflected calls of a breeding adult when flushed. These calls are also higher-pitched and a third shorter than the equivalent calls of Common Ringed Plover C hiaticula. Background: Mallard Anas platyrhynchos and Zitting Cisticola Cisticola juncidis.

Calls of a passing migrant, flying away in a straight line. The calls later in the recording sound slightly less piercing. This is not only due to the sound being quieter from a distance: the harmonics also become weaker. Background: Tundra Bean Geese Anser serrirostris.
Wing sounds and some calls, gradually descending in pitch due to the Doppler effect, as a pair flies past.
Hooting of a male in open Holm Oak Quercus ilex woodland, with large pools here and there following heavy rain. Background: Mallard Anas platyrhynchos and Tawny Owl Strix aluco.
Sounds of four mice feeding on wholemeal bread then scampering up and down the back of a fridge (little mice with clogs on?).
Mice presumably of this species vocalising while feeding in hazelnut and hornbeam scrub. Background: a hazelnut falling to the ground.

Song of a male, singing from an exposed perch. Its mate is nearby, collecting nest material. Background: Black-headed Gull Chroicocephalus ridibundus, Eurasian Skylark Alauda arvensis and Meadow Pipit Anthus pratensis.
Song of a male. Background: flight calls of Eurasian Bittern Botaurus stellaris.
Song of a male. Background: Siberian Chiffchaff Phylloscopus tristis and Siberian Rubythroat Calliope calliope.
Several short songs.
